'''''A viuvinha''''' ('''''The Little Widow''''') is a novel written by the [[Brazil]]ian writer [[José de Alencar]]. It was first published in 1857. [[Luis de Barros]] adapted it into [[A Viuvinha (film)|a film]] in 1914.<ref>Robert Stam and Randall Johnson. "[http://www.ejumpcut.org/archive/onlinessays/JC21folder/BrazilStamJohnson.html Beyond Cinema Novo]". ''[[Jump Cut (journal)|Jump Cut'']] 21 (1979): 13-18.</ref>

In the story, a young Brazilian man plans to marry a young woman he met in a church. On the day before the wedding, however, he learns that he has squandered his inheritance and let the company he owns go bankrupt. The man follows through with the ceremony, but then fakes suicide and flees to the United States. He lives in the United States for three years, slowly recovering his fortune, then returns to Brazil to reunite with his bride, who has remained faithful to him.<ref>Muriel Nazzari. ''[https://books.google.com/books?id=UJtQanKSYMQC&pg=PA156&dq=%22jose+de+alencar%22+%22a+viuvinha%22&client=firefox-a&sig=ACfU3U15fPhoZgKcqbNJI6NQUUOkje3crA Disappearance of the Dowry: Women, Families, and Social Change in São Paulo]''. Stanford University Press, 1991. 156.</ref>

