==Media==

===TV movies===
{{Main|Billy & Mandy's Big Boogey Adventure|Billy & Mandy: Wrath of the Spider Queen|Underfist: Halloween Bash}}
Three [[TV movies]] were made for the series. The first one was called ''Billy & Mandy's Big Boogey Adventure'' and was released on DVD in April, 2007.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.cduniverse.com/productinfo.asp?pid=7361167|title=Billy & Mandy's Big Boogey Adventure DVD|work=[[CD Universe]]|accessdate=May 26, 2012}}</ref> Common Sense Media gave the movie 2/5 stars and is meant for kids over the age of 8 calling it "undeniably gross and just as undeniably funny".<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.commonsensemedia.org/movie-reviews/billy-and-mandys-big-boogey-adventure|title=Billy and Mandy's Big Boogey Adventure|work=[[Common Sense Media]]|accessdate=May 26, 2012}}</ref> DVDverdict.com gave the movie a good review as well.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.dvdverdict.com/reviews/billyandmandy.php|title=Billy And Mandy's Big Boogey Adventure (Review)|work=[[DVD Verdict]]|accessdate=May 26, 2012|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120306022110/http://www.dvdverdict.com/reviews/billyandmandy.php|archivedate=March 6, 2012|df=}}</ref>

A second movie, ''Wrath of the Spider Queen'', was also released in 2007. It was based on a spider queen from Grim's distant past, who tries to take revenge on him because she was meant to be the reaper. Meanwhile, keeping up with the spider theme, Billy learns to love his spider son Jeff.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt1075544/combined|title=Wrath of the Spider Queen|work=[[Internet Movie Database|IMDb]]|accessdate=May 26, 2012}}</ref>

On October 12, 2008, a third and final spin-off movie, titled ''Underfist: Halloween Bash'', premiered. The movie's primary focus is on Irwin, Jeff the Spider, Hoss Delgado, General Skarr, and Fred Fredburger accidentally coming together to defeat an invasion of chocolate bar monsters, led by an evil marshmallow bunny, on Halloween night.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.bcdb.com/cartoon/107731-Underfist_Halloween_Bash.html|title=Underfist: Halloween Bash|work=[[Big Cartoon DataBase|BCDB]]|accessdate=May 27, 2012}}</ref>

===Music===
The score composers for the series are [[Gregory Hinde]], [[Drew Neumann]] and [[Guy Moon]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.gregoryhinde.com/|title=Gregoryhinde resume|work=www.gregoryhinde.com|accessdate=2012-05-27}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.drewneumann.com/DN_Credits.php|title=Drew Neumann Credits|work=[[Drew Neumann|DrewNeumann.com]]|accessdate=May 27, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://movies.nytimes.com/person/103349/Guy-Moon|title=Guy-Moon|work=[[The New York Times]]|accessdate=May 27, 2012}}</ref> In addition, two songs were made for the show by [[Aurelio Voltaire]], the episode "Little Rock of Horrors", which parodies the musical ''[[Little Shop of Horrors (musical)|Little Shop of Horrors]]'', features a song titled "[[BRAINS!]]"<ref name="Amazon.co.uk">{{Cite web|url=https://www.amazon.co.uk/Brains-From-Adventures-Billy-Mandy/dp/B004F9RE9M|title=Brains! (From The Grim Adventures of Billy and Mandy)|work=[[Amazon.com]]|accessdate=May 27, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.cartoonnetworkasia.com/video/grim_billy_mandy/little-rock-of-horror|title=Little Rock of Horror|work=[[Cartoon Network]]|accessdate=May 27, 2012|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120613182651/http://www.cartoonnetworkasia.com/video/grim_billy_mandy/little-rock-of-horror|archivedate=June 13, 2012|df=}}</ref> and, in ''[[Billy & Mandy's Big Boogey Adventure]]'', the song "[[Land of the Dead (Voltaire song)|Land of the Dead]]" is played in the opening credits.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.aq.com/gamedesignnotes/tag/grim-adventures-of-billy-and-mandy|title=New Voltaire Album!|work=[[AdventureQuest Worlds]]|accessdate=May 27, 2012}}</ref> Both songs are a part of the album ''Spooky Songs For Creepy Kids''.<ref name="Amazon.co.uk"/> The season two episode "Battle of the Bands" also featured the song "Darkness" by metal band SPF 1000. There was also an instance at the end of the Christmas special entitled "Billy & Mandy Save Christmas", where the end credits music is the song "[[Round and Round (Ratt song)|Round and Round]]" by heavy metal band [[Ratt]].

===Video game===
{{Main|The Grim Adventures of Billy & Mandy (video game)}}
A video game inspired by the series was developed by [[Midway Games]], and released on October 2, 2006.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.bbfc.co.uk/ADM231785/|title=The Grim Adventures of Billy & Mandy (Video game)|work=[[British Board of Film Classification|BBFC]]|accessdate=May 26, 2012}}</ref> It is a 3D fighting game. The video game received fair to good reviews: [[GameSpot]] gave it a 6.6/10 by Greg Mueller, he goes on to say that while it is fun for the "first few hours" and has "Fast-paced gameplay" the game action "gets old quickly" and has a very short story mode.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.gamespot.com/the-grim-adventures-of-billy-and-mandy/reviews/the-grim-adventures-of-billy-and-mandy-review-6162195/|title=The Grim Adventures of Billy & Mandy Review|publisher=[[GameSpot]]|accessdate=May 26, 2012}}</ref> [[IGN]] gave the game a good score of 7.2/10 highlighting its presentation and appeal.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://ps2.ign.com/articles/739/739790p1.html|title=The Grim Adventures of Billy & Mandy (Video game review)|publisher=[[IGN]]|accessdate=May 26, 2012}}</ref> [[Metacritic]] gave the game a rating of 61/100 based on 10 critic reviews.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.metacritic.com/game/wii/the-grim-adventures-of-billy-mandy|title=The Grim Adventures of Billy & Mandy Wii|publisher=[[Metacritic]]|accessdate=May 26, 2012}}</ref>

